1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,080
Imagine that the person who remembers every small household detail is unavailable for three days.

2
00:00:06,080 --> 00:00:11,040
Good intentions are not enough when school pick up, pet care, an elder check-in,

3
00:00:11,040 --> 00:00:15,600
a bill reminder, and trusted home access all depend on one person.

4
00:00:15,600 --> 00:00:22,000
This is Sahaaya, a family continuity planner built for the OpenAI Build Week apps for your life category.

5
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:27,120
It turns a short household brief into a clear, family-owned continuity plan.

6
00:00:27,120 --> 00:00:31,040
For this demo, every person and fact is fictional.

7
00:00:31,040 --> 00:00:37,280
First, Sahaaya maps five responsibilities and attaches each one to a cited source fact.

8
00:00:37,280 --> 00:00:41,200
It also identifies the questions that the family still needs to answer.

9
00:00:41,200 --> 00:00:44,960
Next, we rehearse a 72-hour absence.

10
00:00:44,960 --> 00:00:49,440
The planner surfaces an availability collision before anyone relies on the plan,

11
00:00:49,440 --> 00:00:54,480
and it explicitly excludes passwords, payment credentials, and door codes.

12
00:00:54,480 --> 00:00:57,360
The key design principle is human control.

13
00:00:57,360 --> 00:01:04,240
Sahaaya proposes assignments, but every responsibility stays pending until a person explicitly approves it.

14
00:01:04,240 --> 00:01:08,160
Compilation remains blocked until all five decisions are made.

15
00:01:08,160 --> 00:01:13,040
After approval, Sahaaya produces separate candidate checklists for the people involved.

16
00:01:13,040 --> 00:01:18,960
It then runs deterministic checks, exact responsibility count, known evidence citations,

17
00:01:18,960 --> 00:01:23,600
allowed assignments, explicit approvals, and the fictional replay boundary.

18
00:01:23,600 --> 00:01:29,520
ASHA-256 receipt makes the demonstrated plan reproducible.

19
00:01:29,520 --> 00:01:35,600
Codex accelerated the product workflow, architecture, tests, and browser verification.

20
00:01:35,600 --> 00:01:43,760
An optional server-only GPT-5.6 proof uses the responses API with structured outputs and storefalls.

21
00:01:43,760 --> 00:01:48,080
GPT-5.6 helps extract grounded suggestions.

22
00:01:48,080 --> 00:01:51,680
Deterministic application code remains responsible for approvals,

23
00:01:51,680 --> 00:01:57,600
verification, and export. Sahaaya never sends messages, triggers emergency services,

24
00:01:57,600 --> 00:02:02,640
or offers medical, legal, financial, or safeguarding advice.

25
00:02:02,640 --> 00:02:06,400
It is a planning aid for a calm, human-reviewed handoff.

26
00:02:06,400 --> 00:02:11,040
Sahaaya, when you cannot be there, your circle knows what to do.

